dv: narration told me how character was feeling
Narration told me about traumatic events
I could relate to the emotions the character was going through because I've been through the same before. That was the driving emotion for me.
Lack of realism. I was acutely aware of her no being real due to appearance and it felt less immersive because of that

The character felt quite unreal. There were many glitches in the visual display such as irregular gaps between the hair. Also, the character was very static and always showed the same set of non-verbal cues, which also felt quire unreal. I struggled to associate the person I was hearing the story about with the VR character.
the fact she was a women and i could relate to her situation/struggled helped me to empathise with her

They seemed familiar. Their clothes, face, hairstyle, and body language seemed...not unexpected. I think that helped me empathise with them. The unfamiliarity of the situation was distracting, so it was hard to focus on the words past the novelty of the VR experience.

The time is too short for me to feel feelings from a stronger.
The character's look is kind of simple that I have some difficult to see her as a real person.
The outlook of the character and the environment around is clean and easy, made me feel comfortable and safe, which is helpful to concentrate on the character and feel her.
The animation quality of the character would have presented a slight mental block from empathising, had I not been engrossed by the narration.
May be I can talk to her, give her help or warmly huge.
the eyes seemed to like have an odd clip effect or static ish - so when focusing on their eyes or face it made it harder to engage. but their body movement felt good and natural in the environment
There wasn't anything stopped me. I felt empathy naturally, as the virtual world felt very immersive.

Her face did not change (neutral to almost a smiling expression) and the third person monotonous narration created an emotional distance from the character. I did find her body language to be very human (shifting from side to side) however beyond that I had trouble reading any signs of emotion from the virtual character at all!
I don't think I go as much detail of he assault to fully evoke my empathy
Seeing someone helped put a face to the narration, but the lack of an environment, combined with the inexpressiveness of the character, hindered my ability to associate the character to the story.
Having the previous knowledge it was a virtual character and not someone 'real'

Their movement was static:
- Gaze (saccades, shifts, fixation, and so on)
- Head movement
- Facial expressions
- Aliveness (body animations like changing movement, breathing in at varied rates)
- Realism (it might be me personally but I feel when something looks more photorealistic and is harder to distinguish from a human then it's movements and attention capture my attention more; but I have also found stylised characters to be effective as well)
- The voice of the narrator might have influenced me since they sounded slightly monotone
The story telling is somewhat similar what my friend had experienced at her work place, it connected and made me empathetic towards the virtual character
The story was what made me empathise the most, along with their body language/expression
Nothing much going on when looking at the face of the character.

very aware that it was an avatar/sim so for me that means it didn't really extend into my emotional space\nalso not really any visual context, no real expression on the avatar, only body language and as was passive/non-interactive
Her face expression. I keep watching her but can't feel any emotional change. It makes me feel that's totally not her story.
The simplicity of the scene provided little context to empathise with the character. A more realistic scene such as a supermarket would have aided with empathising
I had not experienced the same things as her and I thought I would have done different things than her.

It's hard to empathise with a person who doesn't look like a person. It's not that she had a neutral expression, it's that everything about her was neutral, so devoid of personality that she seemed less real than a painting.
I have had a similar experience when i was younger; however, the way i dealt with it was different than the virtual character

I found the auditory experience more immersive than the visual experience, helping me to create a video reel of the character's supposed memories in my mind's eye. The fact that the character model was much shorter than an average human kind of took away from the realism of the experience though.

little eye engagement, not in the sense of looking away, but that i felt the eyes werent active. would have helped to be at least eye level with the avatar, as i was looking at them from an odd above angle even once i tried to move back and adjust my perspective

The character seemed like an NPC, with a constant movement and facial expressions the same. This made me feel like it's not real. Also, the narration tone and pace didn't felt much in sync with the emotions of the virtual character.
lack of body language indicating any of what was being narrated happened. It felt like a picture was being held up. The lack of facial expression drew me to look around more.

The facial expression and demeanour of the character seemed to reflect well the emotions of someone going through what was described. She looked traumatised and in her own head, kind of shell shocked\nThe character being still and stationary prevented me empathising fully because it was clear that it was inanimate, although that's no an issue with the actual model itself.
lack of body language or facial expression, lack of interaction
